Completed questions 240–250 with comprehensive notes, definitions, and mistake review. Focused on disaster recovery metrics, common web vulnerabilities, hacktivism, risk tracking, web application firewalls, and high availability solutions.

🔑 Topics Covered
🚨 Disaster Recovery & Availability
RPO (Recovery Point Objective)
Defines how much data loss is acceptable (time-based).
RTO (Recovery Time Objective)
Defines how quickly systems must be restored.
BTO (Business Time Objective)
Maximum acceptable downtime before major business impact occurs.
🌐 Web Application Security
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
Injects malicious scripts into web pages.
Executes in victim’s browser → data theft/session hijacking.
Web Application Firewall (WAF)
Protects web apps by filtering HTTP traffic.
Blocks attacks like:
SQL injection
XSS
Data exfiltration attempts
🎯 Threat Actors
Hacktivism
Attacks driven by political/social motives.
Focus on disruption or messaging rather than profit.
📊 Risk Management
Risk Register
Tracks vulnerabilities, likelihood, impact, and mitigation strategies.
Helps prioritize security efforts.
⚙️ High Availability
Load Balancing
Distributes traffic across multiple servers.
Prevents downtime and improves scalability.
Ensures continued service if one server fails.
🧠 Key Takeaways
Understand differences between RPO, RTO, and BTO
Know how XSS works and its impact on users
WAF is critical for web-layer protection
Risk registers help prioritize and manage vulnerabilities
Load balancing = availability + fault tolerance
